The Apostolic Fathers and the apologista of the second century furnish us with no additional information. St. Justin, in his description of the initiation of the neo- phytes,l speaks only of the first act, that is, baptism with water ; the Bactriae of the Apostles does the same.

We must come down to the time of Severus, about the year 200, before we find any definite mention of the anointing.2 Tertullian and St. Hippolytus,l especially the former, speek with a precision which leaves nothing to be desired. Tertulliau describes the rites of initiation in several places, and wrote a special treatise upon baptism. He states that this rite should be administered bya bishop, or, with his delegated authority, by priests and deacom, and that in certain cases it might even be conferred by a lay person The candidate had to prepare himself for it by prayer, festings, and holy vigila. It was usually administered at Eester or dudng the fifty days following.
